    <section class="row">
        <p>As an alternative, when teaching the telling of time on an analogue clock or creating circle graphs, consider thinking about the circumference as a wrapped number line.  This allows students to unwrap the number line to create a linear representation that can be more easily equi-partitioned.</p>
        <figure class="margin-bottom">
                <img src="/images/research/supportDocs/RectanglesNumberLinesCircles/recNumLinesCircle-6.jpg"  class="img-responsive margin-auto" />
        </figure>
        <p>The central angle of 360° can also be used as the referent for partitioning a circle, which would be useful to students studying spinner probability. The arrow of a spinner rotates around the central angle of 360° and the partitions of the spinner are based on equal partitions of this angle rather than the areas of the partitions. The following spinners demonstrate this difference.</p>
