                        <tr>
                            <td>
                                <figure class="margin-bottom">
                                    <img src="/images/research/supportDocs/RectanglesNumberLinesCircles/recNumLinesCircle-8.jpg"  class="img-responsive margin-auto" />
                                </figure>
                                <p>When asked to determine a fraction between <abbr title="one third" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>3</sub></span></abbr> and <abbr title="two third" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>2</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>3</sub></span></abbr>, this student chose to use a circle. Their workrevealsdifficulty partitioning acircle into equal sectionsofthirds and fifths.The size of each circle is slightly different and the regions being compared are not aligned, making it difficult to accurately compare.</p>
                                <p>Although the student correctly states “ <abbr title="two fifths" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>2</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>5</sub></span></abbr> is also between <abbr title="one third" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>3</sub></span></abbr> and <abbr title="two third" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>2</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>3</sub></span></abbr> “, this thinking is based upon counting non-equal regions.</p>
                            </td>
                            <td>
                                <figure class="margin-bottom">
                                    <img src="/images/research/supportDocs/RectanglesNumberLinesCircles/recNumLinesCircle-9.jpg"  class="img-responsive margin-auto" />
                                </figure>
                                <p>When asked to determine a fraction between <abbr title="one third" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>3</sub></span></abbr> and <abbr title="two third" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>2</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>3</sub></span></abbr>, this student used stacked number lines. It is easier to create wholes that are clearly equivalent when using number lines. Furthermore, it is easier to line up the fractions for accurate comparison.  Stacked number lines allow for comparing fractions with different denominators.</p>
